This program can be used to authenticate against an SQL database using the BSD
authentication framework. Currently PostgreSQL and MySQL is supported.

After installation the auth style name will be -sql. You can use it after you
configured a login class in login.conf(5) to use this auth style, and created a
configuration file for the authentication program.

The configuration file ignores any line which doesn't start with a recognized
configuration option.
Example configuration file with all of the usable options:

PostgreSQL specific options:
pgsql_dbconnection=dbname=bsd_auth user=bsd_auth password=bsd_auth
pgsql_table=bsd_auth
pgsql_user_col=username
pgsql_pass_col=password

MySQL specific options:
mysql_host=
mysql_port=
mysql_db=bsd_auth
mysql_user=bsd_auth
mysql_pass=bsd_auth
mysql_table=bsd_auth
mysql_user_col=username
mysql_pass_col=password
mysql_key=
mysql_cert=
mysql_ca=
mysql_capath=
mysql_cipher=

digest_alg=sha256


Explanation:
pgsql_dbconnection:	This can include:
			host, hostaddr, port, dbname, user, password, sslmode,
			etc...
			For more information:
			http://www.postgresql.org/8.4/static/libpq-connect.html
			Search for PQconnectdb, and read the recognized
			parameters. Any parameter can be given here as
			keyword=value pairs, separated by spaces.
pgsql_table:		The table name in the database which contains the
			username and password columns.
pgsql_user_col:		The column's name which contains the username.
pgsql_pass_col:		The column's name which contains the password.

mysql_host:		Host name or IP address.
mysql_port:		Port number for a TCP/IP connection.
mysql_db:		Database's name which contains the user/pass.
mysql_user:		Username used for connecting to the database.
mysql_pass:		Password used for connecting to the database.
mysql_table:		Table's name which containts the user/pass.
mysql_user_col:		The column's name which contains the username.
mysql_pass_col:		The column's name which contains the password.
mysql_key:		
mysql_cert:		
mysql_ca:		
mysql_capath:		
mysql_cipher:		
For the MySQL parameters' valid or default values please read the MySQL
documentation here:
http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/mysql-real-connect.html
For the MySQL SSL parameters' valid or default values please read the MySQL
documentation here:
http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/mysql-ssl-set.html

digest_alg:	The message digest algorithm in which the password field is
		hashed in the password column.
		You can use any digest which is supported by your OpenSSL
		library. For more information, enter `openssl dgst -h` on the
		command line.


Example login.conf(5):

sql:\
	:auth=-sql,passwd:\
	:x-sql-cfg_file=/etc/auth/sql.conf:\
	:tc=default:


The config file parameter is optional. If you omit it, the default will be used,
which is /etc/login_sql.conf.
